Choice under uncertainty is when a person facing a choice is not certain of the possible outcomes or their probability of occurring. [S6] The standard way to model how people choose under uncertain condition, is by using expected utility. [S7] In order to calculate expected utility, a utility function 'u' is developed in order to translate money into Utility. [S8] Therefore, if a person has '{\displaystyle x}' money, their utility would be {\displaystyle u(x)}. [S9] This is explored further when investigating potential "prospects". [S10] A prospect, in this context, is a list of expected payoffs and their probabilities of occurring. [S11] A prospect is summarised using the form;

{\displaystyle ProspectA=(p\_{1},x\_{1};p\_{2},x\_{2};...;p\_{n},x\_{n})}

The overall expected value of the prospect (A) is subsequently expressed as;

{\displaystyle V(A)=\sum \_{n=1}^{n}p\_{i}x\_{i}}

The expected utility, U(A), of the prospect is then determined using the below formula;

{\displaystyle U(A)=\sum \_{n=1}^{n}p\_{i}u(x\_{i})}

The utility function is convex for a risk-lover and concave for a risk-averse person (and subsequently linear for a risk-neutral person). [S12] Subsequently, it can be understood that the utility function curves in this way depending on the individual's personal preference towards risk. [S13] Below is an example of a convex utility function, with wealth, '{\displaystyle x}' along the x-axis and utility, '{\displaystyle u(x)}' along the y-axis. [S14] The below graph shows how greater payoffs result in larger utility values at an increasing rate. [S15] Showing that the person with this utility function is "risk-loving". [S16] Alternatively, below is an example of a concave utility function, with wealth, '{\displaystyle x}' along the x-axis and utility, '{\displaystyle u(x)}' along the y-axis. [S17] The below graph again display's an individual's utility function, however this time lower payoffs have a larger utility with respect to the original payoff (or "wealth") value. [S18] The utility values, although still increasing, do so as a decreasing rate. [S19] Showing that this person is "risk-averse". [S20] It is important to note that for prospect theory value functions, risk-seeking behaviour can be observed in the negative domain {\displaystyle x<0}, where the functions are convex for {\displaystyle x<0} but concave for {\displaystyle x>0}. [S21] ## Psychology


### Child personality traits' effect on adulthood â€“ What traits contribute to risk-seeking? [S22] In a study done by Friedman et al. [S23] (1995), they found significant evidence to support that low childhood conscientiousness contributed heavily to adulthood mortality. [S24] Those who were high in conscientiousness as a child were 30% less likely to die in their adulthood. [S25] Ultimately, their findings solidified that low levels of childhood conscientiousness predict risk seeking, and risk-seeking increases the chance of accidental death. [S26] Though risk-seeking deteriorates with age, risky exposure to abusive substances in adolescence can lead to lifetime risk factors due to addiction. [S27] Conscientious individuals are subject to greater internal impulse control which lets them think out risky decisions more carefully, while those low on conscientiousness are more likely to endanger themselves and others by risky, or sometimes even criminal behaviour. [S28] ### Psychometric paradigm
